<div id="main_content">
	<h2>Virtual Reality Helps UCF Clinic Treat With Anxiety Disorders (With Video)</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Chad Binette
		
		<span class="date">Sept. 17, 2008</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: 345px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/1000/NE1554/en_US/virtualfull.jpg" height="226" width="345"  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: Jacque Brund</p>
			
			<p>The simulation of an airline flight allows clients to experience the airport terminal, boarding a plane, taking off, turbulence and landing.</p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004173deb0ca011c7073ab7d00f09">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:">Anxiety Disorders Clinic</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-3910 </li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:dbeidel@mail.ucf.edu">Deborah Beidel, Clinical Psychology</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-3918</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:cbinette@mail.ucf.edu">Chad Binette, News and Information</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-6312</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.psych.ucf.edu/labs_anxiety.php">Anxiety Disorders Clinic</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>New virtual reality equipment will help the University of Central Florida&rsquo;s Anxiety Disorders Clinic treat a wider variety of people with debilitating anxiety disorders.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Wearing head-mounted displays, clients can experience airline flights, giving a speech in front of a large crowd or other activities that are difficult to set up as real scenarios. The soothing voice of a psychologist seated at an adjacent computer helps clients describe their fears and gradually overcome them.&nbsp;</p>
<p>&ldquo;If people are afraid of flying, we have the capability to walk them through a terminal, get on a plane and make the plane take off,&rdquo; said Deborah Beidel, the UCF Psychology professor who directs the clinic. &ldquo;We can even create lightning and thunder within the virtual reality.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The clinic, staffed by Clinical Psychology faculty and doctoral students, is recruiting adults for a treatment program funded by the National Institute of Mental Health. Adults who fear giving speeches to large groups or interacting with others at work may qualify for this treatment program. Another specialty treatment program helps children with severe shyness, some of whom may refuse to go to school as a result of their fears.</p>
<object width="333" height="260"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/EGnj_TaHQ1w&hl=en&fs=1"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/EGnj_TaHQ1w&hl=en&fs=1" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowfullscreen="true" width="333" height="260"></embed></object>
<p>Anxiety disorders affect as much as 20 percent of the population and are the second-most common of psychological disorders, following substance abuse. Anxiety disorders can involve a specific fear such as heights or bridges, or the worries may be more general.&nbsp; Some people have worries that are far in excess of their basis in reality.</p>
<p>Beidel said anxiety disorders usually are best treated by exposing clients to their fears. In some cases, it can be easy to create a real scenario to help someone overcome an anxiety. A child afraid of dogs can be introduced to a friendly dog, for example. Virtual reality makes it much easier to expose people to other anxieties &ndash; such as flying or speaking in front of a large group of people.</p>
<p>The Anxiety Disorders Clinic is located in the Psychology Building on the north end of UCF&rsquo;s main campus in East Orlando. The clinic focuses on behavioral approaches to therapy and does not prescribe medication.</p>
<p>Treatment for adults with social phobia is free through the National Institute of Mental Health program. Treatment for children with severe shyness is also available without a fee. Fees for clients with other anxiety disorders are based on their ability to pay.</p>
<p>Beidel started the clinic when she arrived at UCF last year as a professor and director of the doctoral program in Clinical Psychology. She has treated and studied anxiety disorders for 22 years, most recently at the Penn State College of Medicine and Hershey Medical Center.</p>
<p>Determining when a fear should be considered an anxiety disorder isn&rsquo;t always easy. Beidel said anxiety disorders significantly impair performance on the job or in the classroom or the ability to hold meaningful social relationships.</p>
<p>Most people will be nervous before they give a speech in front of a large group. Someone who suffers from an anxiety disorder will change jobs or their college majors to avoid giving a speech at work or school. People who suffer from a social phobia may choose a job they hate simply because it doesn&rsquo;t require interacting with anyone else.</p>
<p>One study under way at the Anxiety Disorders Clinic involves children who suffer from selective mutism, a social phobia in which they can speak when they are alone or with family but refuse to speak in public. The clinic uses special equipment that can help assess those children by examining their pulse rate and blood pressure in different situations and helping them become more comfortable.</p>
<p>In addition to social phobias, another common disorder among children is separation anxiety disorder, which often occurs at the start of a school year.</p>
<p>Children suffering from separation anxiety will experience more than a few tears or a little trouble sleeping. Severe stomach or headaches, refusing to go to school or refusing to leave the house without their parents are signs that children may have an anxiety disorder, Beidel said. Other children with anxiety disorders may have fears that are greatly out of proportion to their current situation, such as worrying about whether they will be accepted at Harvard University when they are in the third grade.</p>
<p>For more information about the clinic, call 407-823-3910 or go to <a href="http://www.psych.ucf.edu/labs_anxiety.php">www.psych.ucf.edu/labs_anxiety.php</a>.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>UCF Stands For Opportunity:</strong> The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 6th largest in the nation with more than 50,000 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information, visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
